  "response": "The finding for `src/assets/check-icon.png` is `crime_00025` (\"Icon-Sized Raster\"). Its dimensions, quoted verbatim from the evidence:\n\n> \"dimensions: 32 × 32 px (≤ 64 threshold both sides)\"\n\nWhy a new SVG indicator beats another PNG at this size:\n\n- **DPI scaling.** A 32×32 PNG has exactly 32×32 pixels. On a 2x retina display it renders at 64 device-pixels (interpolated, fuzzy); on 3x it gets worse. SVG re-rasterizes at the actual device resolution every time, so it stays crisp on every screen — the finding's own remediation note says \"same render at every DPI.\"\n- **Smaller bytes.** A status indicator (check, dot, arrow) is a handful of vector paths. The SVG markup typically beats the PNG's PNG-encoded raster + headers — even before considering that you'd otherwise need to ship `@2x` and `@3x` PNG variants to cover hi-DPI.\n- **One source of truth.** Copying the PNG pattern means committing to a fixed pixel resolution per status; if design later wants the indicator at 20px or 24px, you re-export from the design tool. With SVG the same file works at any size.\n- **Color/state changes are CSS, not new files.** A hover/disabled/error variant of an SVG indicator is `currentColor` or a class swap; the PNG version requires a separate exported asset per state.\n\nThe check-icon.png itself is flagged precisely because it locked into a single resolution — copying that mistake for a new indicator just compounds it.",
